<br>
I had sought refuge in Highpass, where I had hoped I might work on my brewing in peace, but it was not to be....  Zenogias insisted upon seeing me, he claimed he had something for me, and I reluctantly agreed to meet him.  But when he found me... he threw me to the ground and slashed my wrist, then slashed his own and held our wounds together fast so that our blood might flow into one another....  I could only look on in horror, powerless to stop him yet fearing the outcome of this act which he claims has united us forever.<br>
<br>
When it was done, he left me, and disappeared.<br>
<br>
I knew I must tell Mlain what had happened, and I did, I told him everything: I confessed how I had loved him and had never wanted anyone to know, how I had grown to care about Zenogias believing that Mlain could never return my feelings for him and how Zenogias now would not let me go, and I told him what Zenogias had done to me, there, in Highpass.<br>
<br>
I suppose it was then that Mlain decided Zenogias must die.  He asked me to send a message to Zenogias, to arrange for him to go to the Arena where Mlain could kill him once and for all, and I did.... I told Zenogias that I had to see him again, to be with him, where it all began, in the arena in Neriak.  I feared Zenogias would easily see through my feeble attempt at deception, as I am not used to such ways, but I hoped his desire to be with me would prevail over any suspicions he might have.<br>
<br>
He came to the arena but knew immediately that Mlain was waiting for him....  In desperation I tried to claim that I had brought Mlain there so that Zenogias could kill him as he had once sworn to do, but it was useless.  They began to do battle but did not fight to the death, Zenogias claiming that since Mlain had not fought him when he had wanted to, he would now have to wait until Zenogias was ready to fight him.  I could only look on in horror.<br>
<br>
When Mlain had gone I could stand it no longer, I lashed out at Zenogias in rage and pain, telling him how I had tried to deceive him, to lure him to his death, that he had lost.  I fled to the temple but he followed me even there, despite my cruel words I still could not drive him away.  We spoke for hours as we used to do, and I hope now he understands, about me, and Mlain, and that Zenogias and I can never be together the way he would want.<br>
<br>
I await Mlain's return and hope that he has not come to doubt me as well....<br>
<br>
